a $100 tip in it for you.

548
00:26:16,778 --> 00:26:17,992
Excellent.

549
00:26:18,494 --> 00:26:21,381
Victory.
The night
is finally going my way.

550
00:26:21,841 --> 00:26:23,640
Wilson, toss me a soda.

551
00:26:37,741 --> 00:26:39,707
Shall we go somewhere
to talk?

552
00:26:40,544 --> 00:26:41,841
House is an ass.

553
00:26:41,967 --> 00:26:43,891
But he obviously needs
pain medication,

554
00:26:44,017 --> 00:26:45,314
and how much pain
one person feels

555
00:26:45,398 --> 00:26:47,741
is not a call
the government
should be making.

556
00:26:47,866 --> 00:26:49,833
So you think
I'm a bureaucrat
with a badge

557
00:26:49,875 --> 00:26:52,050
following
some arbitrary guideline.

558
00:26:52,636 --> 00:26:53,849
Yeah, I do.

559
00:26:54,519 --> 00:26:58,494
So you're saying
I should just trust him.
Do you?

560
00:26:58,619 --> 00:27:00,084
You're not qualified
to make that...

561
00:27:00,126 --> 00:27:02,008
I'm not sure
you are, either.

562
00:27:02,050 --> 00:27:03,933
I've been a cop for 20 years.

563
00:27:04,017 --> 00:27:05,063
And not a day goes by

564
00:27:05,063 --> 00:27:09,289
that someone doesn't try
to sell me
some self-serving story.

565
00:27:10,167 --> 00:27:12,008
If you had my job,
you'd know.

566
00:27:13,347 --> 00:27:14,979
Everybody lies.

567
00:27:21,841 --> 00:27:23,891
I think
you've run out of relatives.

568
00:27:24,519 --> 00:27:26,192
So, it's my turn.

569
00:27:31,088 --> 00:27:32,887
Why did you become a doctor?

570
00:27:32,971 --> 00:27:34,393
That's the big question?

571
00:27:35,146 --> 00:27:37,029
I give you complete license
to humiliate me

572
00:27:37,113 --> 00:27:38,410
and that's the best
you can do.

573
00:27:38,452 --> 00:27:41,423
Well, okay, let's discuss
the wonder of the human body.

574
00:27:41,464 --> 00:27:43,640
No, no, no.
You're a curious guy.

575
00:27:44,351 --> 00:27:46,987
You like to figure things out,
why not go into research?

576
00:27:47,029 --> 00:27:48,619
Why work with people when you

577
00:27:49,582 --> 00:27:51,004
obviously hate people?

578
00:27:52,594 --> 00:27:53,975
Oedipal fixation.

579
00:27:54,100 --> 00:27:55,398
I was seeking
my mother's love

580
00:27:55,439 --> 00:27:57,490
and she thought that Ben Casey
was just the dreamiest...

581
00:27:57,531 --> 00:28:00,962
Okay, fine. You don't think
you'll need
any more answers from me?

582
00:28:01,255 --> 00:28:02,845
Give me a hard time.

583
00:28:11,716 --> 00:28:13,264
When I was 14,

584
00:28:14,519 --> 00:28:16,736
my father was stationed
in Japan.

585
00:28:17,490 --> 00:28:20,084
I went rock-climbing
with this kid from school.

586
00:28:20,126 --> 00:28:23,389
He fell and got injured
and I had to bring him
to the hospital.

587
00:28:25,021 --> 00:28:26,946
And we came in through
the wrong entrance

588
00:28:26,987 --> 00:28:28,996
and passed this guy
in the hall.

589
00:28:30,418 --> 00:28:31,799
He was a janitor.

590
00:28:32,176 --> 00:28:34,017
My friend came down
with an infection

591
00:28:34,100 --> 00:28:36,234
and the doctors didn't know
what to do.

592
00:28:37,197 --> 00:28:38,452
So they brought in

593
00:28:40,084 --> 00:28:41,423
the janitor.

594
00:28:44,059 --> 00:28:45,649
He was a doctor.

595
00:28:47,029 --> 00:28:48,912
<i>And a buraku.</i>

596
00:28:50,251 --> 00:28:52,343
One of Japan's untouchables.

597
00:28:53,598 --> 00:28:57,280
His ancestors
had been slaughterers,
gravediggers.

598
00:28:58,494 --> 00:28:59,665
And this guy,

599
00:29:01,423 --> 00:29:04,059
he knew that he wasn't
accepted by the staff,
didn't even try.

600
00:29:04,059 --> 00:29:07,197
He didn't dress well,
he didn't pretend
to be one of them.

601
00:29:08,661 --> 00:29:10,293
The people around that place,

602
00:29:10,418 --> 00:29:12,929
they didn't think
he had anything they wanted,

603
00:29:15,146 --> 00:29:16,946
except when they needed him.

604
00:29:18,243 --> 00:29:20,000
Because he was right.

605
00:29:21,925 --> 00:29:24,184
Which meant
that nothing else mattered.

606
00:29:25,230 --> 00:29:27,448
And they had to listen to him.

607
00:29:36,360 --> 00:29:37,406
Thank you.

608
00:29:38,703 --> 00:29:40,251
(MACHINES BEEPING)

609
00:29:41,213 --> 00:29:43,640
Need 20 milligrams of diazepam
in a syringe.

610
00:29:51,297 --> 00:29:53,222
Heartbeat's irregular
and accelerating.

611
00:29:53,305 --> 00:29:54,770
He's at 200.
He's gonna crash.

612
00:29:54,854 --> 00:29:55,983
Allergic reaction
to the diazepam?

613
00:29:56,067 --> 00:29:57,029
Better hope so.

614
00:29:57,113 --> 00:29:59,665
It's either that
or his heart's done.

615
00:30:06,904 --> 00:30:09,205
What happened
on the night of the fire?

616
00:30:12,803 --> 00:30:16,151
Yeah. I'm sure
it's a stressful,
emotional question.

617
00:30:16,276 --> 00:30:17,364
Suck it up.

618
00:30:20,418 --> 00:30:23,096
My wife
had taken a sleeping pill
and gone to bed.

619
00:30:23,096 --> 00:30:24,100
It was Christmas Eve.

620
00:30:24,142 --> 00:30:26,987
I let Kyle pop corn
in the fireplace.

621
00:30:27,950 --> 00:30:30,962
He managed to knock loose
some tinder.

622
00:30:31,757 --> 00:30:33,347
Wrapping paper caught on fire.

623
00:30:33,389 --> 00:30:35,439
It spread so fast.

624
00:30:35,690 --> 00:30:37,322
I got Kyle out and...

625
00:30:38,285 --> 00:30:40,000
When I went back in for...

626
00:30:44,310 --> 00:30:45,983
You're a disappointment.

627
00:30:47,531 --> 00:30:50,837
You act as though
you don't need anybody,
you...

628
00:30:50,879 --> 00:30:52,887
You just blame your son
for what happened.

629
00:30:52,887 --> 00:30:55,690
I don't blame him.
He was a 12-year-old boy.

630
00:30:55,732 --> 00:30:57,573
You don't blame a kid
for an accident.

631
00:30:57,699 --> 00:30:59,498
Then what are we doing here?
Why aren't you with him?

632
00:30:59,498 --> 00:31:01,255
Because it wouldn't matter.

633
00:31:01,339 --> 00:31:04,142
I failed
to keep my family safe.

634
00:31:04,184 --> 00:31:07,866
I couldn't stop the fire,
I couldn't save my wife,

635
00:31:07,950 --> 00:31:11,506
now you want me
to stick around watching
while I fail to save my son.

636
00:31:11,590 --> 00:31:13,975
Thank you so much
for waking me up.

637
00:31:20,795 --> 00:31:23,013
How did your son
dislodge the tinder?

638
00:31:24,017 --> 00:31:25,105
God...

639
00:31:28,452 --> 00:31:30,335
He dropped the popcorn tray.

640
00:31:30,418 --> 00:31:33,431
He had been complaining
it was too heavy,
I should have listened.

641
00:31:33,515 --> 00:31:36,778
And the hit-and-run,
walking the pissy dog.

642
00:31:36,904 --> 00:31:38,285
That happen at night?

643
00:31:38,326 --> 00:31:40,084
I think so, yeah, why?

644
00:31:40,126 --> 00:31:42,427
Car accident
after the Phillies lost.

645
00:31:42,469 --> 00:31:43,849
Night game?

646
00:31:46,151 --> 00:31:47,866
Ragged-red fiber.

647
00:31:47,950 --> 00:31:49,372
It's an inherited condition.

648
00:31:49,456 --> 00:31:52,427
Dropping things,
muscle weakness,
poor night vision.

649
00:31:52,510 --> 00:31:56,067
Makes people seem
uncoordinated,
accident-prone, careless.

650
00:31:56,151 --> 00:31:58,661
It's transmitted
in mitochondrial DNA

651
00:31:58,745 --> 00:32:00,586
so it only passes
through the mother.

652
00:32:00,628 --> 00:32:03,682
Your wife's family
weren't drunks,
they were sick.

653
00:32:03,933 --> 00:32:05,774
It wouldn't have
affected his liver.

654
00:32:05,816 --> 00:32:07,197
The kid is a drunk.

655
00:32:07,280 --> 00:32:08,452
He thinks that
he killed his mother

656
00:32:08,494 --> 00:32:10,502
and turned his father
into a vegetable.

657
00:32:10,544 --> 00:32:12,594
I might have
a few shots myself.

658
00:32:13,724 --> 00:32:14,812
<i>Foreman.</i>

659
00:32:14,895 --> 00:32:17,699
Test his DNA
for ragged-red fiber.

660
00:32:17,741 --> 00:32:19,372
<i>It's not gonna...
Here's a thought.</i>

661
00:32:19,456 --> 00:32:22,343
Why don't we not assume
that the test is negative
until we actually do it?

662
00:32:22,427 --> 00:32:25,690
House, the kid
has severe cardiomyopathy.

663
00:32:26,569 --> 00:32:28,996
Alcoholic,
no shot at a transplant.

664
00:32:29,331 --> 00:32:32,343
So yeah,
maybe you figured out why,
good for you, but

665
00:32:33,933 --> 00:32:35,774
he's gonna die anyway.

666
00:32:46,444 --> 00:32:47,615
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

667
00:33:00,586 --> 00:33:02,762
I want to give
Kyle my heart.

668
00:33:06,360 --> 00:33:11,004
This thing, whatever it is,
you said he gets it
from the mother.

669
00:33:11,088 --> 00:33:12,218
My heart's fine.

670
00:33:12,218 --> 00:33:15,523
And it could go on being fine
for the rest of your life.

671
00:33:15,607 --> 00:33:18,494
Yeah, it's not like
he's gonna
do anything with it.

672
00:33:18,619 --> 00:33:19,916
Well, you woke him up once,

673
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:22,594
maybe someone'll come up
with some other answer.

674
00:33:22,762 --> 00:33:25,230
We've both seen breakthroughs
no one expected.

675
00:33:26,820 --> 00:33:29,833
And ragged-red fiber's
treatable, but not curable.

676
00:33:30,502 --> 00:33:33,096
Even if he gets your heart,
there's no guarantee.

677
00:33:35,481 --> 00:33:36,736
He's my kid.

678
00:33:38,368 --> 00:33:39,540
No!

679
00:33:39,582 --> 00:33:41,464
Did you really expect
a different answer?

680
00:33:41,464 --> 00:33:45,188
